snippet.textDisplay:
The dagger reveal seemed to speak to something much larger than the characters and events themselves, and I have little doubt in my mind that it was a reference to either The Whills (Star Wars gods) that are so in tune with the universe and balancing everything out (past, present, and future) that they manipulated events in the past to fulfill this moment in the present so that balance could be achieved... or something involving time travel, but the dagger reveal seems much more along the lines of being related to 'puppet masters' behind the scenes, which is basically what The Whills are; a metaphor for both writers of stories and the various elements that naturally move a story (or life) along.

The Sith holocron showing where the largest concentration of Dark is in relation to its location isn't that ridiculous of a McGuffin, as it has practical use in locating a Dark Side user who's become too powerful, with just enough ambiguity to it that it's unclear who previously possessed either one, or even who invented them, or what purpose they served. For all we could guess, it's a balancing tool given to both the Dark and Light users of a certain time to ensure a Sith couldn't become too powerful in the event that their power was consolidated into a single point, like it is with Palpatine.

Finally, JJ mentioned in several interviews that there's always been a plan, even if it was a foggy one, so all these people out there saying 'you need a plan' are pretty much saying nothing. Palpatine being revealed in the third act is an EXCELLENT ass reveal, but I think the only mistake they made was telling the audience BEFORE the movie came out. I suspect it was because of the backlash against TLJ to get people's attention back to Star Wars, but if NOBODY knew Palpatine was gonna be in the final movie, every person saying it felt lazy would have thought it was one of the greatest plot twists in film history. It LOOKS like pathetic fan service in the movie itself because THAT'S WHAT IT WAS FORCED TO BE BEFORE THE MOVIE EVEN CAME OUT.

EDIT: the reveal that Dark Side users continually improve with each successful generation to eventually become consolidated into a single entity is pretty much the ONLY thing that makes sense in regard to the question of 'what happens to Dark Side users when they die?' Light Side users get consumed by (and become one with) the midichlorians in their cells (linking themselves into the Force itself), and Dark Side users get consumed by (and become one with) the next generation in an attempt to create the most powerful offspring possible with enhanced midichlorians, and it would only be a matter of time before Dark Side users began to betray the 'rule of two' in order to obtain more power by consuming other users outside of the 'rule of two,' eventually leading to someone like Palpatine. It really is subtly genius, and not nearly as lazy or poorly-thought-out as most people seem to think it is.

snippet.textDisplay:
Agree with your points, other than I don't think JJ should have made the third movie into damage control. Instead of being a prick and deciding to undo everything Rian did, he should have just accepted TLJ exists and run with it. I know a lot of people didn't like the movie, but I think the "reveal" that Rey really was a nobody was one of the best in the entire SW franchise. They should have kept that, instead of going with some 12 yo fanfic writer's wet dream.


And the force healing coming from nowhere was also retarded, but I could have accepted it except for the very end for Ben using it to bring Rey "back". First, why did she even die? Like everything else in the movie, this is left unexplained, other than plot demands it because drama. Second, how does Kylo now know how to do this? And not just heal but straight up resurrect? Seriously??? Lastly, it kills him, because, again, reasons. Redemption=death, I suppose. I don't see why Ben had to die. I would have been much happier with either Rey staying dead, or they both live. Rey being the only one to live is just absurd. While I generally disagree with most who call Rey a Mary Sue, this was pretty much the straw that broke the camel's back. I guess Disney is just straight up too afraid of having anything bad happen to or said of a woman, and thus Rey is just infallible and immortal.


And yeah, her taking the name Skywalker was also insulting. What connection did she have at all? If Ben had lived and they went on to have uber powerful force babies, and they both take up the name Skywalker, sure I could buy that. But she's just like, yolo, Skywalker now. And how insulting is it that Ben is the one to die for her, but he gets ZERO mention at the end of the movie? No force ghost, no funeral pyre like Anakin, absolutely nothing. I think that speaks to JJ's complete disrespect for the entire franchise more than anything.


Overall the movie was enjoyable, sure, but the more I think about how fanficky it is and its inability to actually produce a satisfying trilogy just makes me pretty sad.

snippet.textDisplay:
How the Disney Wars movies were made:



The Force Awakens

Mickey Mouse: Ok people, the nerds liked the original trilogy, but a lot of them hated the prequels. The prequels had new ideas, many jedis and new vehicles, so our movie is going to have none of those. Let’s make a carbon copy of A New Hope, revert every character to what their status was in that movie (like Han being single again just because), let’s go back to one jedi, use the same vehicles, the same type of enemy as in the original trilogy and that’s it. The nerds are going to be so fucking drunk on nostalgia that no one is going to notice that this movie hasn’t got a single original idea in it.

The Last Jedi
MM: Ok, TFA was a big hit, but some people are starting to notice it was a carbon copy of A New Hope. So yeah, in this one let’s go batshit crazy. Rian, ok, we’ll let you introduce you cool new ideas and subvert every mystery TFA left dangling.



The Rise of Skywalker
MM: Ok, shit, we went too fucking crazy. We broke the nerds in half. Let’s go back to nostalgia. Let’s bring back every character we haven’t killed, let’s market it as the end of a generational saga (even though we all know we’ll see plenty more Skywalkers in the future), let’s improvise something about Rey’s parents, let’s try to make as if the 3 main characters have some sort of relationship.

BTW, I wrote this before watching The Rise of Improvisation.
